<TITLE> MPs 'soon' to use laptops in parliament </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov17 (bdnews24.com)--The MPs will use laptops in parliament and take questions emailed by people 'soon', the speaker has said. "Legislators will be allowed to carry and use laptops inside parliament soon but no one will be allowed to enter the house with grenade, bomb and arms," speaker Abdul Hamid said with his trademark humour. He spoke as chief guest at the launch of five-day 'BCS ICT World' fair hosted by Bangladesh Computer Samity in the capital. He said parliament is being digitised and steps are on to let the media other than BTV air parliamentary proceedings live. "Steps are also being taken so that the common people can watch parlimentary proceedings live from anywhere and email questions to the MPs." Hamid said internet should be made available to the educational institutions and computer to the students. Commerce minister Faruq Khan said one of the prime campaign pledges of the government is to spread information technology across the country. The governement will initiate all steps so that the new generation can reap full benefits of ICT. The minister said, "The website of commerce ministry is being updated to receive questions emailed by common people." State minister for science and information Yafes Osman said the government will do everything possible to help the ICT sector flourish. He called for bringing young generation under modern information technology-based education system to build a 'Digital Bangladesh' by 2021. Grameenphone CEO Oddvar Hesjedal also spoke in the programme chaired by IT specialist and BCS president Mostafa Jabbar. The fair seats 32 pavillions and 80 stalls where 65 firms are paticipating with different ICT products, mostly laptops. A number of seminars have been arranged under the banner of 'Digital Bangladesh Summit 2009' in the fair which will remain open from 10 am to 8pm until Nov 21. bd
